<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-07-13</title>

<p>Over the past few days the embodied-AI and world-model literature has pushed in three directions at once: scaling video pretraining with Mixture-of-Experts, diagnosing what world models actually learn, and making multi-agent world models real-time. This run chases the strongest of those threads. The unifying question is whether these systems are learning physics or merely learning to extrapolate visually consistent motion. The answer, so far, is sobering: we can build bigger, faster, and more controllable world models, but a direct diagnostic shows that at least one major world-model family imagines kinematically rather than dynamically. The actionable insight is that the field needs better probes, not just bigger models.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> "Imagined Rollouts Are Kinematic, Not Dynamic" is the clearest seed for research this run. It turns a vague complaint about compounding error into a falsifiable diagnostic, releases code and checkpoints, and the headline signature reproduces cleanly on CPU. If the finding generalizes, it reframes how we should train and evaluate world models.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Scaling video pretraining for embodied AI</h1>

<p>LingBot released two companion systems in the same week: LingBot-Video, a 30 B sparse-MoE video diffusion model, and LingBot-World 2.0 (Infinity), a real-time causal world model. They share a team and a data-centric philosophy, but code inspection shows they are architecturally distinct. Together they let us ask what it takes to repurpose internet-scale video generation for embodied intelligence.</p>

<h2>LingBot-Video and LingBot-World 2.0</h2>
<p><b>Authors:</b> Ma et al. / Gao et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.07675">HF 2607.07675</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.07675">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/robbyant/lingbot-video">Code</a></p>

<p>LingBot-Video is a non-causal diffusion transformer built for text-to-image, text-to-video, and image-to-video. Its distinguishing choice is scale through sparsity: a 30 B total / ~2.9 B active MoE with 128 routed experts, top-8 routing, group-limited routing, shared experts, and online load-balancing bias. We counted parameters analytically from the released Diffusers config and confirmed ~30.1 B total and ~2.89 B active per token. A smaller dense 1.3 B variant and a 480p→1080p refiner are also released.</p>

<p>The data engine is the other half of the claim. The authors profile videos along structural, semantic, motion, camera, and quality axes, annotate with VLMs and specialized scorers, and use a 50 k-leaf knowledge graph plus an action tree to drive distribution-aware sampling. The five-stage curriculum ends with more than 70 k hours of robot manipulation, navigation, and egocentric footage blended with web video. Post-training uses GRPO with six de-coupled reward models: vision quality, text-video alignment, dynamic degree, motion coherence, human-motion consistency, and physical plausibility.</p>

<p>LingBot-World 2.0 is a different beast. It is a dense 14 B causal DiT derived from Wan2.2, conditioned on camera Plücker embeddings and chunk-wise text prompts. Training uses a hybrid causal/bidirectional attention mask (MoBA) and conditional flow matching. Distillation combines consistency distillation with Distribution Matching Distillation run over long self-rollouts, which is meant to suppress compounding drift. The released artifact is the distilled 14 B causal-fast model; the causal-pretrain and 1.3 B variants are marked TODO.</p>

<p>What the code makes clear is that the two systems are siblings, not parent and child. LingBot-World 2.0 is not initialized from LingBot-Video weights; it is a Wan2.2-style dense causal transformer with its own conditioning. The shared DNA is conceptual: structured captions, embodied footage, cascaded refinement, and a focus on physical plausibility.</p>

<p><b>Reported numbers.</b> LingBot-Video scores 0.620 on RBench (open-source SOTA) and 40.4 on Physics-IQ Verified I2V. The MoE 30B-A3B is 2.59× faster than a dense 14 B and 3.18× faster than a dense 30 B on a 1 M-token sequence. LingBot-World 2.0's claims are mostly qualitative: hour-long 720p generation at 60 fps, with no standard VBench or Physics-IQ numbers yet.</p>

