<h1>Diagnosing long-horizon world-model failure</h1>

<p>While LingBot and MIRA are building bigger and faster world models, a diagnostic paper from TUM asks a more basic question: when these models fail over long horizons, what kind of error is compounding? Their answer is that current world models tend to imagine kinematically, not dynamically. The claim is operationalized with a metric and a protocol that can be run on any action-conditioned world model.</p>

<h2>Imagined Rollouts Are Kinematic, Not Dynamic</h2>
<p><b>Authors:</b> Schäfer et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.05966">HF 2607.05966</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.05966">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/TUM-AVS/iKCE">Code</a></p>

<p>The paper starts from a classical-mechanics distinction. <b>Kinematic</b> motion is described by position, velocity, and acceleration time series. <b>Dynamic</b> motion requires the forces and constraints that produced it. A world model that imagines kinematically will produce internally consistent trajectories that nonetheless ignore physical regime changes such as a friction drop.</p>

<p>The diagnostic tool is the <b>imagined Kinematic-Consistency Error (iKCE)</b>. For an imagined rollout <latex>\{\hat{x}_t\}_{t=0}^{T}</latex> with kinematic state <latex>\hat{x}_t</latex>, define</p>

<p><latex>\text{iKCE} \;\doteq\; \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \bigl\|\, \hat{x}_{t+1}^{\text{WM}} \;-\; \mathrm{kin}\bigl(\hat{x}_t^{\text{WM}}\bigr) \,\bigr\|^{2}.</latex></p>

<p>For the walker identity view used in the headline experiment, the kinematic null is a one-step constant-velocity update on root height and vertical velocity:</p>

<p><latex>\hat{x}_t = \begin{bmatrix} z_t \\ \dot{z}_t \end{bmatrix}, \quad \mathrm{kin}(\hat{x}_t) = \begin{bmatrix} z_t + \Delta t \, \dot{z}_t \\ \dot{z}_t \end{bmatrix}, \quad \Delta t = 25\,\text{ms}.</latex></p>

<p>The counter-intuitive reading is that <b>low iKCE is bad</b>: it means the imagined state is exactly the kinematic continuation of the previous state. A dynamic imaginer would deviate from this null when physical conditions change.</p>

<p>To break the ambiguity, the authors pair iKCE with a perturbation protocol. They sweep MuJoCo sliding friction by a multiplier <latex>\mu \in [0.1, 1.7]</latex>, crossing the empirically determined gait-collapse boundary near <latex>\mu \approx 0.20</latex>. They run two channels: real DMC physics driven by the trained DreamerV3 policy, and imagined rollouts from the DreamerV3 world model conditioned on five perturbed observations. They also run a positive control: adding Gaussian noise to joint positions directly corrupts the kinematic state and should raise iKCE.</p>

<h3>Reproduction</h3>
<p>We cloned the official diagnostic repository and the pinned DreamerV3 PyTorch port, downloaded the released checkpoint with curl, and ran the friction sweep on CPU. The headline signature reproduced cleanly. The world-model iKCE stayed flat across the friction sweep while real-physics iKCE dropped as friction decreased.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:ikce:friction-sweep]]</p>

