<p>The positive control also behaved as expected: adding joint-position noise raised WM iKCE from 2.35 × 10⁻³ at σ=0.00 to 2.81 × 10⁻³ at σ=0.30, confirming the model is not globally insensitive. Finally, we recomputed the log-log friction slope at horizons T ∈ {8, 16, 32, 64}. The dynamic signature only emerged at T=64, matching the paper's claim that the diagnostic must be run longer than the embodiment's gait period.</p>

<h3>What it means</h3>
<p>The diagnostic adds a third layer to the world-model failure surface. The Dreamer line stabilizes latent representations; MBPO bounds error compounding through short branched rollouts; iKCE tests what the latent representation actually contains. A model can satisfy the first two while still being dynamically blind. The fix is not simply more parameters or longer training: the latent state needs dynamic features such as contact state, friction, and mass distribution.</p>

<p>The main caveat is scope. The evidence is from one task and one model family. Generalizing to humanoids, driving, or generative video world models is open. And iKCE is structural, not predictive: a model could be dynamic in unmeasured dimensions while looking kinematic on root height.</p>

