<h1>Multiplayer interactive world models</h1>

<p>If LingBot is about scaling and the iKCE paper is about diagnosis, MIRA is about controllability under multi-agent action streams. It asks whether a learned world model can simulate a fast, contact-rich 3D game for multiple players in real time, with each player's actions conditioning the shared future.</p>

<h2>MIRA: Multiplayer Interactive World Models with Representation Autoencoders</h2>
<p><b>Authors:</b> Hu et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.05352">HF 2607.05352</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.05352">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/mira-wm/mira">Code</a></p>

<p>MIRA simulates 2v2 Rocket League. The game is fast, partially observed from each player's first-person view, and dominated by car-ball contact. The model is a 5 B parameter latent diffusion transformer. It is trained on 10,000 hours of gameplay recorded with publicly available bots, and at rollout it generates four synchronized views at 20 fps on a single Nvidia B200.</p>

<p>The key design choice is the representation autoencoder. The encoder starts from a frozen DINOv3-L/16 backbone, aggregates intermediate layers, and compresses through a learned 3-D convolutional bottleneck to 32 latent channels at 10 Hz. The decoder is a 28-layer ViT-XL with factorized space-time attention. The loss is L1 reconstruction plus LPIPS plus DINO latent consistency, with adaptive gradient weighting. The autoencoder is deterministic and continuous; there is no VQ and no GAN.</p>

<p>The world model operates on the codec latent grid. It is a factorized axial transformer with spatial self-attention (full) and temporal self-attention (causal). Training uses diffusion forcing: each latent frame is noised independently to a random flow-matching level, and the model predicts the velocity field back to data. A few-step self-distillation objective (PSD) lets inference run in one or two function evaluations per frame. The multiplayer conditioning tiles the four per-player latent grids vertically, adds learned player embeddings, and processes the tall grid with joint attention. During training, per-player action dropout forces the model to stay coherent under arbitrary subsets of active players.</p>

<h3>What the ablations say</h3>
<p>The codec ablations are the most informative part of the paper. A latent-space model beats pixel-space baselines by a wide margin (gFID 10.7 vs. 81–105). A frozen DINOv3-L feature extractor beats a from-scratch extractor even though the from-scratch extractor reconstructs sharper single frames in PSNR (29.7 vs. 32.2). The pretrained features give a smoother latent geometry: small errors stay semantically valid instead of compounding into visual drift. This is a strong empirical argument that the choice of latent space matters as much as the generative architecture.</p>

