<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>

<p><b>Scale, data, and latent space are the current levers.</b> LingBot scales parameters and data. MIRA shows that the latent space choice can matter more than raw scale. Both point to the same lesson: the substrate on which the world model learns is as important as the model itself.</p>

<p><b>But scale does not guarantee dynamics.</b> The iKCE diagnostic is a warning. A world model can be large, fast, controllable, and visually stable while still failing to represent friction, contact, and other regime variables. The field currently lacks standardized dynamic probes; iKCE is one candidate, but it needs to be applied beyond walker-walk and DreamerV3.</p>

<p><b>Real-time and long-horizon are being decoupled.</b> LingBot-World 2.0 and MIRA both use distillation to make inference cheap enough for real-time interaction, while keeping the base model expressive. This split between teacher (quality) and student (speed) is becoming standard.</p>

<p><b>The evaluation gap is widening.</b> We have RBench and Physics-IQ for video quality, FVD and gFID for world-model frames, and now iKCE for dynamic content. None of them alone is enough. A useful next step would be to run iKCE-style probes on LingBot-World 2.0 and MIRA, or to apply MIRA's action-recovery and game-state probes to LingBot's embodied videos.</p>

<p><b>Open questions for follow-up.</b> Does the DINOv3-L codec recipe transfer to real-world robotics, where pretrained visual features may be less reliable? Can iKCE be extended to visual-latent world models and generative video models? And what would a training objective that penalizes regime invariance look like?</p>
